    metrics:{enrolment:"127",teachers:"19",sanctioned:"27",vacancies:"8",nonTeaching:"8",gender:"Co-ed",building:"Govt"},
    insights:[
      "<b>A girls' access cliff at Class 10.</b> Fine-arts training ends at grade 9 and the co-ed school runs only to Class 10; the Cl. 11–12 junior college is boys-only and sits in a completely separate building with its own residential block and facilities — unusual compared with the society's other schools. Girls who want to continue must travel far for 11–12, making this a real dropout driver and gender-access gap.",
      "<b>A specialist mission that truncates itself.</b> The school admits by audition across eight art forms but only three are currently staffed (drawing, vocals, dance), and the art form is dropped from the timetable entirely at grade 10. Even so, many students keep practising on their own and go on to pursue it onward as their foremost choice.",
      "<b>Among the worst-condition buildings seen.</b> Serious cracks and fallen masonry, old long-faded paint and no repairs in a very long time across all blocks including the separate junior-college building. Repair funds were released but the work has stalled over contractor problems — colliding sharply with the principal's 4.5/5 self-rating of the infrastructure.",
      "<b>Stark girls' residential inequity.</b> Five rooms and a single, inadequate washroom serve close to ~100 girls at full strength. The girls sleep on mattresses on the floor — around 25 to a room — with no beds and reportedly no funds to buy them, while the boys have bunk beds. The girls' block is dark and dingy with no CCTV.",
      "<b>Staffing shortage with improvised residential care.</b> Eight of 27 teaching posts are vacant and 10 of the 19 in post are guest teachers. New recruits are reluctant to take on warden duty, so training falls on senior teachers and there is no structured residential-training programme. The only real feedback loop is academic — a monthly principal-and-RCO review of uploaded student academic profiles.",
      "<b>Gender handled by avoidance.</b> There is no gender sensitization on a co-ed campus of teenagers, and some staff feel the school shouldn't be co-ed or want the sexes separated. A boys-heavy roll plus a boys-only junior college makes for a male-dominated setting. Open questions remain (flagged as gaps, not findings): with mostly male staff, who supports girls on menstrual and sexual health, whether girls feel safe, and whether they move freely to the grounds or stay confined to a cramped block.",
      "<b>No mental-health support for young boarders.</b> Physical health is reasonably covered, but the once- or twice-yearly \"counsellor\" is really a career adviser; there is no psychological counsellor — a gap staff themselves call essential for such young children living far from home.",
      "<b>A genuine bright spot.</b> Parents are engaged through monthly meetings (and flagged infrastructure as their biggest concern), and a student said the teachers take good care of them despite modest facilities — enough that they feel settled rather than wanting to go home."
    ],
